              <h2>How to use the Colorado local sales tax calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose the calculation mode.</strong> Use “tax on top
                  of price” when you know the pre‑tax price. Use “tax included
                  in total” when you only know the final amount paid and want to
                  extract the tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the amount.</strong> Type the purchase price
                  (before tax) or total amount (including tax), depending on the
                  mode.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your local rates.</strong> The state rate of
                  2.9% is prefilled. Add county, city, and special district
                  rates for your location.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate tax”.</strong> The tool shows total
                  tax, total with tax, effective rate, and a full breakdown by
                  jurisdiction.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Colorado sales tax formula</h2>
              <p>Let:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><code>P</code> = taxable price (before tax)</li>
                <li><code>r_s</code> = state rate (2.9% = 0.029)</li>
                <li><code>r_c</code> = county rate</li>
                <li><code>r_city</code> = city / town rate</li>
                <li><code>r_d</code> = special district rate</li>
                <li>
                  <code>R</code> = total rate =
                  <code>r_s + r_c + r_city + r_d</code>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Tax‑exclusive (add tax on top):</strong></p>
                <p>Total tax: \( \text{Tax} = P \times R \)</p>
                <p>Total with tax: \( \text{Total} = P \times (1 + R) \)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Tax‑inclusive (reverse calculation):</strong></p>
                <p>Let <code>T</code> = total amount paid (tax included).</p>
                <p>Taxable price: \( P = \dfrac{T}{1 + R} \)</p>
                <p>Tax portion: \( \text{Tax} = T - P \)</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Understanding Colorado state and local sales tax</h2>
              <p>
                Colorado has a <strong>statewide sales tax of 2.9%</strong>. On
                top of that, counties, cities, and special districts (such as
                RTD, cultural, and transportation districts) can impose their
                own sales taxes.
              </p>

              <p>For any given address, the total rate is usually:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>State: 2.9%</li>
                <li>+ County: varies by county</li>
                <li>
                  + City / town: varies by municipality (including home‑rule
                  cities)
                </li>
                <li>+ Special districts: varies (RTD, cultural, etc.)</li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                Many Colorado cities are <strong>home‑rule</strong> and
                administer their own sales tax separately from the state. That
                means:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  They may have different taxability rules (e.g., for groceries,
                  services, or shipping).
                </li>
                <li>They may require separate licenses and returns.</li>
                <li>The combined rate can change frequently.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Destination‑based sourcing</h3>
              <p>
                Colorado generally uses
                <strong>destination‑based sourcing</strong> for most sales: the
                applicable local tax is based on where the buyer receives the
                goods, not where the seller is located. This is especially
                important for online and delivery sales.
              </p>

              <h2>Examples</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – Tax on top of price</h3>
              <p>Assume:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Taxable price: <code>P = $100.00</code></li>
                <li>State: 2.9%</li>
                <li>County: 1.0%</li>
                <li>City: 3.0%</li>
                <li>Special district: 1.2%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Total rate: \( R = 0.029 + 0.010 + 0.030 + 0.012 = 0.081 \)
                (8.1%)
              </p>
              <p>Tax: \( 100 \times 0.081 = \$8.10 \)</p>
              <p>Total with tax: \( 100 \times 1.081 = \$108.10 \)</p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Reverse calculation (tax included)</h3>
              <p>
                You charged a customer <code>$108.10</code> total and know the
                combined rate is 8.1%. What portion is tax?
              </p>
              <p>Taxable price: \( P = 108.10 / 1.081 \approx \$100.00 \)</p>
              <p>Tax: \( 108.10 - 100.00 = \$8.10 \)</p>

              <h2>What this calculator does well (and what it doesn’t)</h2>
              <p>This calculator is designed to be:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flexible:</strong> You can enter any combination of
                  state, county, city, and district rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bidirectional:</strong> It works both when you know
                  the pre‑tax price and when you only know the tax‑inclusive
                  total.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transparent:</strong> It shows a clear breakdown of
                  tax by jurisdiction.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>However, it does <strong>not</strong>:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Look up official rates for a specific address.</li>
                <li>
                  Determine whether a particular item or service is taxable.
                </li>
                <li>File returns or keep records for compliance.</li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                For official rate lookup and binding guidance, use the Colorado
